[2]
Date: Wed 25 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Times of India, Wed 25 Jun 2003 [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/cms.dll/xml/uncomp/articleshow?msid=41887>

India (Kerala): Dengue Fever and an Undefined Fever Prevalent in Bangalore
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Dengue fever, which caused over a dozen deaths in the city during monsoon
in 2002, has surfaced again following the rains. BCC health authorities
have reported nearly 30 cases over the past 15 days. Some private
practitioners are also reporting, seeing an average of around 6 cases per
week during the same period. No casualties [fatalities?] have been
reported. The incidence seems to be largely from the western side of the
city; areas like West of Chord Road, Basaveshwaranagar. "Every day there
are 2 or 3 cases being reported," says BCC chief health officer Dr
Jayachandra Rao.
The BCC health office issued a notice on Monday, warning about the disease
and asking citizens to prevent water collection in open containers. "Yes,
the disease is back. But unlike last year when most cases were seen after
the rains began, this year we saw a few cases ahead of rain," says
consultant physician and expert on dengue, Dr S.V. Chowti. According to
him, one serious case has been reported so far while several cases, where
blood platelet counts have fallen, have been noticed.
An [undiagnosed] viral fever too is prevailing in the city resulting in
students and employees staying away from workplaces. "Nearly 50 percent of
our trainee nurses have come down with a fever and have been sent home to
Kerala [see the following post - Mod.CP]. We have been seeing 10 to 20
cases over the past 2 weeks," says Dr H. Paramesh, medical director of the
Lakeside Hospital. It starts with a sniffle and develops into a fever where
temperatures are in the range of 103 to 104 degrees Celsius for 2 to 3
days. The patient subsequently experiences extreme tiredness for a few
days, he said. According to Dr B.C. Rao, a general practitioner, this type
of viral fever is quite a common feature during this season and in late
winter in Bangalore. For those with the viral fever the doctors are
prescribing rest, plenty of fluids, warm clothing, and non-oily food.
[Byline: T.A. Johnson]
