Date: Thu 26 Jun 2003
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
Source: Sun Star online, thu 26 Jun 2003 [edited]
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/bag/2003/06/26/news/61.dengue.cases.noted.in.cordilleras.daily.html>

Philippines: Dengue Fever Widespread in the Cordilleras
-------------------------------------------------------
The Department of Health (DOH) in the region said that an average of 61
confirmed dengue cases in the Cordilleras are being reported everyday in
the local papers here. Health experts have renewed their appeal for the
public to be vigilant and for residents to clean their surroundings,
especially during the rainy season, when dengue cases are expected to rise.
This [became apparent] as Dr. Elnoria Bugnosen of the DOH reported that
dengue cases were highest in the city during the months of January and May
2003. "We already have a reported 22 cases in the 6 sentinel hospitals in
the city for the past 6 months," Bugnosen said. Bugnosen stressed that
dengue is a preventable disease.
Only last week, the DOH declared a dengue outbreak in Paracelis, Mt.
Province, following some 107 cases of dengue fever recorded from Jan to May
2003. Regional Director Teresita Bonoan said that an upsurge in dengue
cases reported in the area was noted last month with 51 outpatients and
admittances. Bugnosen said that a team from the Regional Epidemiology and
Surveillance Unit (RESU) was also dispatched to Paracelis in close
coordination with the Provincial Health Office and Mt. Province Provincial
Disaster Coordinating Council. No casualties [fatalities?] have been
reported so far, but some patients remain to be in critical condition,
reports added. The DOH has also coordinated with the different line
agencies to conduct fumigation operations in identified areas in the city
where dengue is most likely to start, especially in schools. In addition,
Bonoan has ordered a massive clean-up drive in barangays all over the
Cordilleras.
Mayor Bernardo Vergara has also ordered the Baguio Health Department to
closely monitor dengue cases in the city, especially in schools. The mayor
added that he would ask City Budget Office to allocate P1-million [USD 18
700] for the campaign against dengue. Dr. Florence Reyes, BHD head,
revealed that their office has already stocked up on medicines for dengue
and chemicals for fumigation.
The City Surveillance and Epidemiology Unit (CESU) of the BHD reported
earlier that there were 25 cases of dengue admissions during the first
quarter of this year as compared to only 7 cases reported in the same
period last year. Dr. Cecilia Brillantes, CESU chief, however, said that
their office is "still on top of the situation."
